<subSubSection pageId="38" pageNumber="637" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="38.[1976,2570,1593,2017]" pageId="38" pageNumber="637">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1976,2131,1593,1622]" pageId="38" pageNumber="637">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="St. Leger, 1929" authorityName="St. Leger" authorityYear="1929" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="38" pageNumber="637" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rosalinda">Gerbillus rosalinda St. Leger, 1929</taxonomicName>
, 
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3864424328" pageId="38" pageNumber="637">145 km SW EI Obeid, Abu Zabad, Kordofan, Sudan.</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[1976,2570,1593,2017]" pageId="38" pageNumber="637">
<taxonomicName authorityName="St. Leger" authorityYear="1929" box="[1980,2217,1711,1740]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="38" pageNumber="637" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rosalinda">Gerbillus rosalinda</taxonomicName>
was considered on mor- phological grounds a distinct species by F. Petter in 1975, D. M. Lay in 1983, and I. Ya. Pavlinov and colleagues in 1990. Although no genetic data are available, D. C. D. Hap- pold in 2013 and A. Monadjem and team in 2015 kept it as a valid species pending further revision. Both Petter in 1975 and
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[1366,2574,2023,2808]" box="[1367,2568,2023,2057]" pageId="38" pageNumber="637">
Monadjem and colleagues 40 years later found it to be very similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1903" box="[2306,2401,2023,2057]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="38" pageNumber="637" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="agag">G. agag</taxonomicName>
. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="38" pageNumber="637" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="637" targetBox="[1596,1600,2783,2808]" targetPageId="38">
<paragraph blockId="38.[1366,2574,2023,2808]" pageId="38" pageNumber="637">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1366,1542,2067,2096]" pageId="38" pageNumber="637">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from a few localities in C Sudan (Kordofan region) and WC Somalia.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="38" pageNumber="637" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="38.[1366,2574,2023,2808]" pageId="38" pageNumber="637">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1366,1615,2149,2174]" pageId="38" pageNumber="637">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 87-106 mm, tail 105-130 mm, ear 13-16 mm, hindfoot 23-27 mm; weight 20-35 g. The 
<taxonomicName authority="Gerbil" authorityName="Gerbil" box="[1832,2068,2181,2215]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="38" pageNumber="637" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rosalinda">Rosalinda Gerbil</taxonomicName>
is a small member of genus having hairy soles of feet. Its general appearance is dark, with rusty-orange dorsal pelage and pure white ventral one. Top of head and nose are rusty-orange, contrasting with white cheeks, chin, throat, limbs and feet. Tail is long (120% of head-body length) and covered with dense short hairs, ending in narrow pencil of dark long hairs. Large auditory bullae (¢.36% of total length of skull).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="38" pageNumber="637" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="38.[1366,2574,2023,2808]" box="[1368,2159,2418,2452]" pageId="38" pageNumber="637">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1368,1479,2418,2452]" pageId="38" pageNumber="637">Habitat.</emphasis>
Dry grasslands of Somali-Masai vegetation zone.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[1366,2574,2023,2808]" box="[1368,1868,2458,2492]" pageId="38" pageNumber="637">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1368,1629,2458,2492]" pageId="38" pageNumber="637">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
No information.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
